00:45:36.790 --> 00:45:37.770 align:middle line:90%
over 2, 000 square miles.

00:45:37.770 --> 00:45:38.645 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --wiped out.

00:45:38.645 --> 00:45:39.770 align:middle line:90%
Did anybody die then?

00:45:39.770 --> 00:45:41.240 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Not confirmed.

00:45:41.240 --> 00:45:43.880 align:middle line:84%
There are reports of at least
one person being blown off

00:45:43.880 --> 00:45:44.710 align:middle line:90%
their porch.

00:45:44.710 --> 00:45:45.900 align:middle line:90%
This is middle of--

00:45:45.900 --> 00:45:46.902 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: This was 190--

00:45:46.902 --> 00:45:47.260 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: 1908--

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:47.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --8.

00:45:47.850 --> 00:45:49.540 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: --in the
middle of Siberia.

00:45:49.540 --> 00:45:52.915 align:middle line:84%
So thankfully, very,
very low population.

00:45:52.915 --> 00:45:53.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:45:53.540 --> 00:45:55.550 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: So we don't think
there were any people killed,

00:45:55.550 --> 00:45:56.770 align:middle line:90%
fortunately, from that.

00:45:56.770 --> 00:45:59.550 align:middle line:84%
There were reports of a herd
of reindeer being scorched,

00:45:59.550 --> 00:46:01.300 align:middle line:90%
but no people, fortunately.

00:46:01.300 --> 00:46:03.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What are the odds
of this other situation that

00:46:03.850 --> 00:46:05.857 align:middle line:90%
occurred again over Siberia--

00:46:05.857 --> 00:46:06.440 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:46:06.440 --> 00:46:09.504 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --I mean, two
spots over Siberia?

00:46:09.504 --> 00:46:10.295 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that strange?

00:46:10.295 --> 00:46:10.580 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:46:10.580 --> 00:46:11.250 align:middle line:90%
That was a big question.

00:46:11.250 --> 00:46:13.400 align:middle line:84%
How come Russia's getting
all the big impacts?

00:46:13.400 --> 00:46:17.535 align:middle line:84%
But when you live in a country
that spans nine time zones,

00:46:17.535 --> 00:46:19.980 align:middle line:84%
that's a lot of fraction
of the area of the Earth

00:46:19.980 --> 00:46:20.750 align:middle line:90%
to catch stuff.

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:24.840 align:middle line:84%
So you're just playing the odds
by having a very large country.

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:26.341 align:middle line:84%
The Pacific Ocean,
by far, gets most

00:46:26.341 --> 00:46:28.423 align:middle line:84%
of the things that impact
the planet Earth, right,

00:46:28.423 --> 00:46:30.070 align:middle line:84%
just by definition
today at least.

00:46:30.070 --> 00:46:32.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would we get hit
and not know about it?

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:33.500 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Oh.

00:46:33.500 --> 00:46:35.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I'm not
saying about seeing it.

00:46:35.210 --> 00:46:38.180 align:middle line:84%
Would the impact occur,
let's say in the ocean,

00:46:38.180 --> 00:46:40.200 align:middle line:84%
and we simply just
don't know about it?

00:46:40.200 --> 00:46:40.950 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Oh, yeah.

00:46:40.950 --> 00:46:42.750 align:middle line:90%
Sure, certainly in the past.

00:46:42.750 --> 00:46:45.710 align:middle line:84%
Today we have the same
network of sensors

00:46:45.710 --> 00:46:48.520 align:middle line:84%
that allowed us to learn so
much about this particular event

00:46:48.520 --> 00:46:49.940 align:middle line:84%
in Russia just a
few months back.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:52.770 align:middle line:90%


00:46:52.770 --> 00:46:56.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is the global network
of infrasound detectors.

00:46:56.760 --> 00:47:00.170 align:middle line:84%
There are, of course,
military satellites orbiting

00:47:00.170 --> 00:47:03.210 align:middle line:84%
the Earth, which are scanning
the edge of the Earth's

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:06.570 align:middle line:84%
atmosphere all the time looking
for interesting infrared

00:47:06.570 --> 00:47:07.572 align:middle line:90%
explosive events, right?

00:47:07.572 --> 00:47:10.030 align:middle line:84%
They have their other reasons
for looking for those things,

00:47:10.030 --> 00:47:11.880 align:middle line:84%
but they certainly
show asteroids as well.

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:14.740 align:middle line:84%
So it's hard for
something of that scale

00:47:14.740 --> 00:47:17.000 align:middle line:90%
to go undetected these days.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:21.936 align:middle line:84%
But certainly the smaller ones,
this desk, or a basketball, it

00:47:21.936 --> 00:47:22.810 align:middle line:90%
happens all the time.

00:47:22.810 --> 00:47:25.310 align:middle line:84%
Things enter all over the place
without us knowing about it.

00:47:25.310 --> 00:47:27.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Daniel,
paint us a scenario.

00:47:27.360 --> 00:47:32.980 align:middle line:84%
An object five miles
wide heading this way,

00:47:32.980 --> 00:47:35.680 align:middle line:90%
and we've got a month's notice.

