there's maybe some--

00:47:55.280 --> 00:47:55.660 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Planning.

00:47:55.660 --> 00:47:56.370 align:middle line:90%
There's planning.

00:47:56.370 --> 00:47:57.953 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: --maybe you
can do something.

00:47:57.953 --> 00:47:59.525 align:middle line:84%
A month out,
absolutely nothing you

00:47:59.525 --> 00:48:01.810 align:middle line:90%
could do about it at that stage.

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:04.860 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be like the
movie "Deep Impact," which

00:48:04.860 --> 00:48:07.116 align:middle line:84%
was a human story
about what people

00:48:07.116 --> 00:48:08.240 align:middle line:90%
did to prepare for the end.

00:48:08.240 --> 00:48:09.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --during
their last moments.

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:09.314 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:48:09.314 --> 00:48:10.440 align:middle line:84%
Do you spend time
with your family?

00:48:10.440 --> 00:48:11.250 align:middle line:90%
Do you go--whatever.

00:48:11.250 --> 00:48:12.110 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be that kind of--

00:48:12.110 --> 00:48:13.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is it a planet killer?

00:48:13.540 --> 00:48:16.580 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Five miles
across is very nearly

00:48:16.580 --> 00:48:19.620 align:middle line:84%
the size of the object that
wiped out the dinosaurs, right?

00:48:19.620 --> 00:48:21.249 align:middle line:84%
That's a civilization
ender, for sure.

00:48:21.249 --> 00:48:21.790 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:48:21.790 --> 00:48:24.170 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: It's
maybe just possibly

00:48:24.170 --> 00:48:26.590 align:middle line:84%
even a species ender
for us at that point.

00:48:26.590 --> 00:48:28.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would there
be any survivors?

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:30.260 align:middle line:84%
I mean, could you
go underground?

00:48:30.260 --> 00:48:31.342 align:middle line:90%
Could you hide?

00:48:31.342 --> 00:48:32.800 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: The problem
with an impact

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:36.280 align:middle line:84%
like that is you can escape the
initial ravages of the impact,

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:40.080 align:middle line:84%
the blast, perhaps scorching
wildfires depending

00:48:40.080 --> 00:48:43.210 align:middle line:84%
on the scale of the impact,
but you can't escape

00:48:43.210 --> 00:48:46.180 align:middle line:84%
the poisoning of the atmosphere,
the heating of the atmosphere.

00:48:46.180 --> 00:48:48.800 align:middle line:90%


00:48:48.800 --> 00:48:51.240 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be long-term
global warming after that,

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:54.780 align:middle line:84%
right, because you're going
to put enough carbon dioxide

00:48:54.780 --> 00:48:59.044 align:middle line:84%
and other greenhouse gases
in the atmosphere to be bad.

00:48:59.044 --> 00:49:01.210 align:middle line:84%
In the short-term, it's
going to be cooling effects.

00:49:01.210 --> 00:49:03.793 align:middle line:84%
You're going to put aerosols in
the atmosphere and dust, which

00:49:03.793 --> 00:49:05.610 align:middle line:84%
is going to be the
nuclear winter scenario.

00:49:05.610 --> 00:49:05.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:06.835 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: So even if
you hide in a cave,

00:49:06.835 --> 00:49:08.945 align:middle line:84%
and you've got a week's
worth of food, that's--

00:49:08.945 --> 00:49:10.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's not
going to help you.

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:10.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:10.430 --> 00:49:12.480 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Not to mention the
fact that the ozone-- we've

00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:13.900 align:middle line:84%
talked about the
ozone layer before.

00:49:13.900 --> 00:49:14.230 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:15.646 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: An object
of that size is

00:49:15.646 --> 00:49:18.200 align:middle line:84%
going to have enough stuff
in it to destroy the ozone

00:49:18.200 --> 00:49:21.934 align:middle line:84%
layer many, many, many
thousands of times over.

00:49:21.934 --> 00:49:24.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And then you
instantly get that effect too.

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:25.140 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: And then
you've got all the UV.

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:26.910 align:middle line:84%
It's just going to
kill plants, and algae,

00:49:26.910 --> 00:49:28.220 align:middle line:90%
and break down the food chain.

00:49:28.220 --> 00:49:29.220 align:middle line:90%
There's no place to go--

00:49:29.220 --> 00:49:31.666 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So if you and
I were on the planet,

00:49:31.666 --> 00:49:32.790 align:middle line:90%
and we're talking together.

00:49:32.790 --> 00:49:35.390 align:middle line:84%
Not that you'd want to you
end your moment with me,

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:38.440 align:middle line:90%
but we're there.

00:49:38.440 --> 00:49:40.060 align:middle line:90%
Do we see something coming in?

00:49:40.060 --> 00:49:40.760 align:middle line:90%
What do we see?

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:41.343 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:49:41.343 --> 00:49:44.820 align:middle line:84%
So an object of that size
coming in for-- that's

00:49:44.820 --> 00:49:46.820 align:middle line:84%
big enough that for
the weeks before,

00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:49.370 align:middle line:84%
you're going to actually
see it in the sky as a star.

00:49:49.370 --> 00:49:49.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:51.750 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: In the few
days before, it's

00:49:51.750 --> 00:49:54.050 align:middle line:84%
going to be a pretty
brilliant star in the sky

00:49:54.050 --> 00:49:56.096 align:middle line:90%
as it approaches you.

00:49:56.096 --> 00:49:57.470 align:middle line:84%
In those moments
as it's entering

00:49:57.470 --> 00:50:00.600 align:middle line:84%
through the atmosphere, its
many, many, many, many suns

00:50:00.600 --> 00:50:03.830 align:middle line:84%
in the sky, bright
enough, hot enough

00:50:03.830 --> 00:50:06.440 align:middle line:84%
that it will spontaneously
ignite any vegetation

00:50:06.440 --> 00:50:09.234 align:middle line:84%
within eye shot of
it over the horizon.

00:50:09.234 --> 00:50:10.150 align:middle line:90%
And then the big boom.

00:50:10.150 --> 00:50:11.108 align:middle line:90%
And then it's all over.

00:50:11.108 --> 00:50:13.687 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Will government tell
us about it if it's that close?

00:50:13.687 --> 00:50:14.270 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:50:14.270 --> 00:50:15.410 align:middle line:90%
That's-- well--

00:50:15.410 --> 00:50:17.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Can you
imagine the chaos

00:50:17.860 --> 00:50:20.056 align:middle line:90%
over the course of a month?

00:50:20.056 --> 00:50:21.430 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Certainly
I think we all

00:50:21.430 --> 00:50:24.990 align:middle line:84%
have the impression that
governments wanting to control

00:50:24.990 --> 00:50:29.010 align:middle line:84%
information the way they
do, there will certainly

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:32.557 align:middle line:84%
be people who will want
to control at least how

00:50:32.557 --> 00:50:33.890 align:middle line:90%
and what information is put out.

00:50:33.890 --> 00:50:35.265 align:middle line:84%
But I'll tell you,
with something

00:50:35.265 --> 00:50:38.120 align:middle line:84%
of that scale with the global
network of amateur citizen

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:40.820 align:middle line:84%
scientists around the planet,
can't hide something like that.

00:50:40.820 --> 00:50:42.380 align:middle line:90%
It's just, there's no hiding it.

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:43.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And would
you go-- would you

00:50:43.410 --> 00:50:45.200 align:middle line:84%
go on the radio
station show with me?

00:50:45.200 --> 00:50:45.620 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah, my--

00:50:45.620 --> 00:50:47.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Coast to Coast, would
you tell me the way it is?

00:50:47.740 --> 00:50:49.323 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: I think
most of my colleagues

00:50:49.323 --> 00:50:52.620 align:middle line:84%
that I work with, our philosophy
is-- we're scientists, right?

00:50:52.620 --> 00:50:54.840 align:middle line:90%
We deal with information.

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:57.130 align:middle line:84%
Our predilection is to
give as much information

00:50:57.130 --> 00:50:59.590 align:middle line:84%
to people as possible so you
have information to work with.

00:50:59.590 --> 00:51:01.980 align:middle line:84%
More information is always
better from that perspective,

00:51:01.980 --> 00:51:03.002 align:middle line:90%
from my perspective.

00:51:03.002 --> 00:51:04.960 align:middle line:84%
Certainly I know there
are people out there who

00:51:04.960 --> 00:51:08.262 align:middle line:84%
would like to not do
that, but everybody

00:51:08.262 --> 00:51:10.470 align:middle line:84%
I know in my community and
the asteroid impact hazard

00:51:10.470 --> 00:51:12.722 align:middle line:84%
community is all about
sharing that information.

00:51:12.722 --> 00:51:14.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You and I
have talked about this

00:51:14.430 --> 00:51:18.010 align:middle line:84%
for in excess of 12 years
about the possibilities

00:51:18.010 --> 00:51:19.959 align:middle line:90%
of these things happening.

00:51:19.959 --> 00:51:21.500 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: And then
we had Chelyabinsk,

00:51:21.500 --> 00:51:23.050 align:middle line:84%
which was what we've
been talking about.

00:51:23.050 --> 00:51:23.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We'd been
talking about it.

00:51:23.980 --> 00:51:25.020 align:middle line:90%
It was right there.

00:51:25.020 --> 00:51:28.510 align:middle line:84%
So is there that
possibility that one day we

00:51:28.510 --> 00:51:32.860 align:middle line:84%
could have a, if not a
planet killer, a city killer?

00:51:32.860 --> 00:51:35.710 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Yeah, certainly
the city killers.

00:51:35.710 --> 00:51:39.950 align:middle line:84%
Fortunately, as I said,
the telescopic surveys

00:51:39.950 --> 00:51:42.560 align:middle line:84%
have done a great job
at the big civilization

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:45.170 align:middle line:90%
enders, the dinosaur killers.

00:51:45.170 --> 00:51:47.020 align:middle line:84%
Now there's always
the possibility

00:51:47.020 --> 00:51:51.650 align:middle line:84%
that a comet nucleus from
the outer solar system

00:51:51.650 --> 00:51:52.650 align:middle line:90%
can drift through.

00:51:52.650 --> 00:51:55.191 align:middle line:84%
Several years ago, we had Comet
Hale-Bopp if you'll remember.

00:51:55.191 --> 00:51:57.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah but, how much
time do we have on that?

00:51:57.910 --> 00:51:59.620 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: That's the
danger of comets

00:51:59.620 --> 00:52:01.870 align:middle line:84%
is they can come from the
outer solar system with only

00:52:01.870 --> 00:52:03.120 align:middle line:90%
a year or two of notice.

00:52:03.120 --> 00:52:04.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You're kidding?

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:05.760 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: And because of
the orbits that they're on,

00:52:05.760 --> 00:52:07.330 align:middle line:84%
there's nothing you
can do about those.

00:52:07.330 --> 00:52:09.040 align:middle line:84%
I mean, really nothing
you can do about those.

00:52:09.040 --> 00:52:10.550 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And how big is a comet?

00:52:10.550 --> 00:52:13.360 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Comet Hale-Bopp
was 50 kilometers across.

00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:14.790 align:middle line:90%
Not 5, 50.

00:52:14.790 --> 00:52:15.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's huge.

00:52:15.680 --> 00:52:16.346 align:middle line:90%
Oh, that's huge.

00:52:16.346 --> 00:52:17.987 align:middle line:84%
That's like a
little tiny planet.

00:52:17.987 --> 00:52:19.820 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: That would
take us back to bacteria

00:52:19.820 --> 00:52:21.860 align:middle line:84%
on the planet,
something of that scale.

00:52:21.860 --> 00:52:26.230 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would that literally
shatter the planet if it hit?

00:52:26.230 --> 00:52:28.790 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: No.

00:52:28.790 --> 00:52:32.480 align:middle line:84%
Even the moon-forming
impact, which was something,

00:52:32.480 --> 00:52:34.830 align:middle line:84%
we think, nearly
the size of Mars

00:52:34.830 --> 00:52:39.290 align:middle line:84%
hitting the proto-Earth on
a glancing, shearing angle.

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:41.210 align:middle line:84%
It certainly was
enough to splash off

00:52:41.210 --> 00:52:44.110 align:middle line:84%
most of the mantle of the
Earth and part of that object.

00:52:44.110 --> 00:52:46.402 align:middle line:84%
But big objects have
so much gravity,

00:52:46.402 --> 00:52:48.860 align:middle line:84%
it's really hard to kind of
really disperse them like that.

00:52:48.860 --> 00:52:51.450 align:middle line:84%
So certainly that
sort of comet impact,

00:52:51.450 --> 00:52:55.240 align:middle line:84%
the Earth as a physical
entity, is going to be fine.

00:52:55.240 --> 00:52:57.320 align:middle line:84%
Biologically, it's not a
good day for the planet,

00:52:57.320 --> 00:52:59.260 align:middle line:84%
but as a physical
entity, no problem.

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:02.030 align:middle line:84%
But those, I have to
say, are extremely--

00:53:02.030 --> 00:53:05.420 align:middle line:84%
comets are only a tiny--they're
like 1% of the impact hazard we

00:53:05.420 --> 00:53:06.330 align:middle line:90%
worry about.

00:53:06.330 --> 00:53:10.440 align:middle line:84%
The real concern now
that we've completed

00:53:10.440 --> 00:53:12.630 align:middle line:84%
the survey for the big
near-Earth asteroids,

00:53:12.630 --> 00:53:15.440 align:middle line:84%
and given the fact that comets
are such a tiny fraction,

00:53:15.440 --> 00:53:18.160 align:middle line:84%
the real concern are
exactly what you said,

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:19.880 align:middle line:90%
the city killers, right?

00:53:19.880 --> 00:53:23.399 align:middle line:84%
And those are what we want
to look for with Sentinel.

00:53:23.399 --> 00:53:25.690 align:middle line:84%
Those are what we want to go
out with other spacecraft,

00:53:25.690 --> 00:53:28.420 align:middle line:84%
and characterize,
and learn more about.

00:53:28.420 --> 00:53:31.470 align:middle line:84%
And those are the objects
that we're still discovering.

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:35.100 align:middle line:84%
We have not yet discovered
most of those objects that

00:53:35.100 --> 00:53:36.540 align:middle line:84%
are in the near-Earth
population.

00:53:36.540 --> 00:53:40.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Mile-long asteroid hits
in the middle of the Atlantic,

00:53:40.080 --> 00:53:43.640 align:middle line:84%
how big is the tsunami on the
eastern coast of the United

00:53:43.640 --> 00:53:44.200 align:middle line:90%
States.

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:46.283 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Mile-wide impact,
those are big tsunamis.

00:53:46.283 --> 00:53:51.030 align:middle line:84%
Those are many, many
10s, probably a couple

00:53:51.030 --> 00:53:53.200 align:middle line:90%
hundred meters high.

00:53:53.200 --> 00:53:54.539 align:middle line:90%
It washes across--

00:53:54.539 --> 00:53:56.830 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It would knock down
every building as it hits.

00:53:56.830 --> 00:53:57.413 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:53:57.413 --> 00:54:00.440 align:middle line:84%
You go along the entire Atl--
basically that tsunami will

00:54:00.440 --> 00:54:02.940 align:middle line:84%
propagate around the world, but
certainly the Atlantic basin

00:54:02.940 --> 00:54:03.200 align:middle line:90%
will--

00:54:03.200 --> 00:54:04.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And how
far in do you think?

00:54:04.890 --> 00:54:05.540 align:middle line:90%
50 miles?

00:54:05.540 --> 00:54:05.860 align:middle line:90%
100 miles?

00:54:05.860 --> 00:54:06.690 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: It depends on
the coastline, right?

00:54:06.690 --> 00:54:09.064 align:middle line:84%
Certain coasts, you'll wash
a lot further in than others,

00:54:09.064 --> 00:54:12.390 align:middle line:84%
but yes, you're talking many,
many, dozens of miles inland.

00:54:12.390 --> 00:54:13.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Devastating
the whole area?

00:54:13.890 --> 00:54:14.473 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Yeah.

00:54:14.473 --> 00:54:15.080 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Done?

00:54:15.080 --> 00:54:17.288 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Well, we saw what
happened in Southeast Asia

00:54:17.288 --> 00:54:18.944 align:middle line:84%
with only a-- that
was meters tall.

00:54:18.944 --> 00:54:20.110 align:middle line:90%
We're talking 10 kilometers.

00:54:20.110 --> 00:54:21.230 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And that
was an earthquake.

00:54:21.230 --> 00:54:22.730 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: That was
an earthquake that

00:54:22.730 --> 00:54:25.642 align:middle line:84%
dropped a little
block in the ocean.

00:54:25.642 --> 00:54:28.070 align:middle line:84%
The tsunami profile
you get from an impact

00:54:28.070 --> 00:54:30.350 align:middle line:84%
is a little different than
those earthquake ones.

00:54:30.350 --> 00:54:34.177 align:middle line:84%
And so we used to worry about
those for smaller impactors.

00:54:34.177 --> 00:54:34.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:54:34.760 --> 00:54:37.760 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: We learned, though,
by studying that process

00:54:37.760 --> 00:54:39.399 align:middle line:84%
that the splash
that you get creates

00:54:39.399 --> 00:54:40.690 align:middle line:90%
a slightly different wave form.

00:54:40.690 --> 00:54:46.072 align:middle line:84%
So the football-field-sized
impactors in the ocean,

00:54:46.072 --> 00:54:48.030 align:middle line:84%
we used to worry about
the tsunamis from those,

00:54:48.030 --> 00:54:49.613 align:middle line:84%
but now we know that
most of that gets

00:54:49.613 --> 00:54:53.980 align:middle line:84%
sucked up on the coastline,
the outer continental shelf.

00:54:53.980 --> 00:54:56.040 align:middle line:84%
The big ones, though,
a mile impactor, that's

00:54:56.040 --> 00:54:57.170 align:middle line:90%
going to go in anyway.

00:54:57.170 --> 00:54:58.022 align:middle line:90%
That's bad.

00:54:58.022 --> 00:55:00.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you still glad
you're doing what you're doing?

00:55:00.480 --> 00:55:02.410 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Absolutely, absolutely.

00:55:02.410 --> 00:55:06.070 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's not just the
hazards from the asteroids.

00:55:06.070 --> 00:55:10.800 align:middle line:84%
These same objects that
are potential impactors

00:55:10.800 --> 00:55:13.175 align:middle line:84%
because they are so
close to the Earth,

00:55:13.175 --> 00:55:14.550 align:middle line:84%
and because it's
so easy for them

00:55:14.550 --> 00:55:17.980 align:middle line:84%
to impact, that also can
conversely mean those

00:55:17.980 --> 00:55:22.240 align:middle line:84%
are the objects that are easier
for us to get to as well.

00:55:22.240 --> 00:55:24.680 align:middle line:84%
And they hold great
promise for exploration

00:55:24.680 --> 00:55:28.420 align:middle line:84%
for, as we discussed,
providing us that place

00:55:28.420 --> 00:55:31.370 align:middle line:84%
to go to expand the human
experience in space,

00:55:31.370 --> 00:55:34.070 align:middle line:84%
the human presence in our
solar system beyond the Earth,

00:55:34.070 --> 00:55:35.540 align:middle line:90%
Moon system.

00:55:35.540 --> 00:55:37.470 align:middle line:84%
Before we go to
Mars, it would be

00:55:37.470 --> 00:55:40.415 align:middle line:84%
great to practice
those techniques

00:55:40.415 --> 00:55:42.220 align:middle line:84%
on another deep
space object that's

00:55:42.220 --> 00:55:43.905 align:middle line:90%
further away than the Moon.

00:55:43.905 --> 00:55:45.960 align:middle line:84%
And those asteroids are
great targets for that.

00:55:45.960 --> 00:55:48.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They say a
comet could hit Mars--

00:55:48.460 --> 00:55:49.290 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Oh, yes.

00:55:49.290 --> 00:55:49.600 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:50.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --sometime next year.

00:55:50.590 --> 00:55:51.440 align:middle line:90%
Is that a real possibility?

00:55:51.440 --> 00:55:52.648 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Comet Siding Spring.

00:55:52.648 --> 00:55:54.310 align:middle line:90%
It's still a possibility.

00:55:54.310 --> 00:55:55.724 align:middle line:84%
It comes down to
this uncertainty

00:55:55.724 --> 00:55:56.890 align:middle line:90%
that we talked about before.

00:55:56.890 --> 00:55:59.710 align:middle line:84%
And in the case of a comet, it's
not the sunlight pushing on it.

00:55:59.710 --> 00:56:02.480 align:middle line:84%
It's the sunlight activating
all those gaseous jets

00:56:02.480 --> 00:56:03.662 align:middle line:90%
on the comet.

00:56:03.662 --> 00:56:04.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Better Mars than us.

00:56:04.870 --> 00:56:06.410 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Better Mars than us.

00:56:06.410 --> 00:56:09.370 align:middle line:84%
In some ways, it would
be a fantastic scientific

00:56:09.370 --> 00:56:09.910 align:middle line:90%
experiment--

00:56:09.910 --> 00:56:10.743 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --to watch.

00:56:10.743 --> 00:56:13.340 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: --to watch
an impact like that.

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:15.875 align:middle line:84%
It would be bad for our
Mars program, space program,

00:56:15.875 --> 00:56:18.099 align:middle line:84%
though, because all of the
space assets we currently

00:56:18.099 --> 00:56:20.140 align:middle line:84%
have at Mars would be in
severe danger from that.

00:56:20.140 --> 00:56:21.223 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're all gone.

00:56:21.223 --> 00:56:23.670 align:middle line:84%
And what about the debris
from the impact for us?

00:56:23.670 --> 00:56:25.800 align:middle line:90%
Could it hit us?

00:56:25.800 --> 00:56:29.667 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: That would provide--
well, you know, it's

00:56:29.667 --> 00:56:31.250 align:middle line:84%
impacts like that
that that do deliver

00:56:31.250 --> 00:56:32.860 align:middle line:90%
Mars meteorites to Earth.

00:56:32.860 --> 00:56:34.705 align:middle line:84%
That would be a longer
time scale thing.

00:56:34.705 --> 00:56:36.330 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that
we would necessarily

00:56:36.330 --> 00:56:38.235 align:middle line:84%
see, in the following
year or two,

00:56:38.235 --> 00:56:40.040 align:middle line:90%
a shower of Mars meteorites.

00:56:40.040 --> 00:56:43.150 align:middle line:84%
But that would certainly
be a new recent impact

00:56:43.150 --> 00:56:46.164 align:middle line:84%
that, over sort of short
term geologic time scales,

00:56:46.164 --> 00:56:48.080 align:middle line:84%
would certainly deliver
stuff to us, no doubt.

00:56:48.080 --> 00:56:49.663 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Wouldn't
that be amazing just

00:56:49.663 --> 00:56:51.890 align:middle line:90%
to be able to watch that happen?

00:56:51.890 --> 00:56:54.880 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Every year two
tons of Mars meteorites

00:56:54.880 --> 00:56:56.482 align:middle line:90%
falls on our planet, right?

00:56:56.482 --> 00:56:57.690 align:middle line:90%
We don't know where they are.

00:56:57.690 --> 00:56:59.230 align:middle line:84%
They're all falling
in the Atlantic.

00:56:59.230 --> 00:57:01.006 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And from how long ago?

00:57:01.006 --> 00:57:01.630 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: From--

00:57:01.630 --> 00:57:03.005 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --millions
of years ago?

00:57:03.005 --> 00:57:03.546 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: On--

00:57:03.546 --> 00:57:04.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Billions?

00:57:04.390 --> 00:57:05.931 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: --on time
scales of millions

00:57:05.931 --> 00:57:07.530 align:middle line:84%
to hundreds of
thousands of years.

00:57:07.530 --> 00:57:07.810 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:57:07.810 --> 00:57:09.210 align:middle line:84%
They've just been
orbiting around,

00:57:09.210 --> 00:57:10.370 align:middle line:90%
and then they get sucked in?

00:57:10.370 --> 00:57:11.078 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Exactly.

00:57:11.078 --> 00:57:12.960 align:middle line:84%
They are just that
many more little bits

00:57:12.960 --> 00:57:15.449 align:middle line:90%
of near-Earth material.

00:57:15.449 --> 00:57:17.740 align:middle line:84%
But it would be certainly
fascinating to actually watch

00:57:17.740 --> 00:57:18.807 align:middle line:90%
an impact of that scale.

00:57:18.807 --> 00:57:20.640 align:middle line:84%
We've never seen something
on a hard surface

00:57:20.640 --> 00:57:21.764 align:middle line:90%
of an object of that scale.

00:57:21.764 --> 00:57:24.040 align:middle line:84%
We can't reproduce
those in the laboratory.

00:57:24.040 --> 00:57:26.350 align:middle line:84%
And we don't yet know
enough about the physics

00:57:26.350 --> 00:57:27.495 align:middle line:90%
to model it in a computer.

00:57:27.495 --> 00:57:30.460 align:middle line:84%
We know a lot of the physics,
but an impact like that

00:57:30.460 --> 00:57:32.500 align:middle line:84%
would certainly help
really nail down

00:57:32.500 --> 00:57:34.809 align:middle line:84%
and constrain
those models better

00:57:34.809 --> 00:57:36.600 align:middle line:84%
to allow us to make
better predictions even

00:57:36.600 --> 00:57:37.850 align:middle line:90%
for the impacts here on Earth.

00:57:37.850 --> 00:57:40.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Will we get better
in the next 5 or 10 years

00:57:40.300 --> 00:57:42.267 align:middle line:90%
for asteroid sighting?

00:57:42.267 --> 00:57:43.100 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Absolutely.

00:57:43.100 --> 00:57:46.650 align:middle line:84%
If Sentinel launches,
we're currently

00:57:46.650 --> 00:57:49.160 align:middle line:90%
targeting 2017 to 2018.

00:57:49.160 --> 00:57:53.190 align:middle line:84%
This infrared mission alone in
the first month of operation

00:57:53.190 --> 00:57:54.800 align:middle line:84%
would discover 20,000
new asteroids--

00:57:54.800 --> 00:57:55.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --that we
don't know about?

00:57:55.640 --> 00:57:56.600 align:middle line:10%
>>DURDA: That we
don't know about.

00:57:56.600 --> 00:57:57.766 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: We've got to do it.

00:57:57.766 --> 00:58:00.649 align:middle line:10%
>>DURDA: Over its lifetime, over
six and a half years orbiting

00:58:00.649 --> 00:58:02.190 align:middle line:10%
around inside the
orbit of the Earth,

00:58:02.190 --> 00:58:04.940 align:middle line:10%
it would find 500,000
new asteroids--

00:58:04.940 --> 00:58:05.980 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: In what size?

00:58:05.980 --> 00:58:08.470 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Down to the things
that are of this concern, down

00:58:08.470 --> 00:58:11.300 align:middle line:84%
to about maybe a third the
size of a football field.

00:58:11.300 --> 00:58:13.110 align:middle line:84%
That's why we want to
launch this mission.

00:58:13.110 --> 00:58:15.660 align:middle line:84%
This mission will
literally completely

00:58:15.660 --> 00:58:18.990 align:middle line:84%
clean up the problem for us in
terms of knowing and predicting

00:58:18.990 --> 00:58:20.240 align:middle line:90%
when these small objects are--

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:22.835 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is there any
reason we won't launch this?

00:58:22.835 --> 00:58:26.830 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: We just need to
build up the funding for it.

00:58:26.830 --> 00:58:29.027 align:middle line:84%
We are privately raising
the money for this mission.

00:58:29.027 --> 00:58:30.610 align:middle line:84%
And that's the only
thing stopping us.

00:58:30.610 --> 00:58:31.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Privately?

00:58:31.190 --> 00:58:31.620 align:middle line:90%
>>DURDA: Privately.

00:58:31.620 --> 00:58:33.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why isn't government
spending the money?

00:58:33.700 --> 00:58:34.730 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: They have
other things to do.

00:58:34.730 --> 00:58:36.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You would think it
would be a great investment.

00:58:36.390 --> 00:58:38.610 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Well, but there are
lots of other great investment

00:58:38.610 --> 00:58:39.318 align:middle line:90%
that NASA has to.

00:58:39.318 --> 00:58:41.541 align:middle line:84%
So I don't want to,
in any way, appear

00:58:41.541 --> 00:58:43.290 align:middle line:84%
to be pointing a finger
at NASA saying you

00:58:43.290 --> 00:58:44.998 align:middle line:84%
guys should be doing
this because there's

00:58:44.998 --> 00:58:47.644 align:middle line:84%
a lot of other things that
they need to be doing as well.

00:58:47.644 --> 00:58:49.810 align:middle line:84%
And so we view ourselves
as sort of just helping out

00:58:49.810 --> 00:58:53.430 align:middle line:84%
with the problem, taking on a
bit of this problem ourselves,

00:58:53.430 --> 00:58:55.940 align:middle line:84%
and letting NASA go on and
do other things that it

00:58:55.940 --> 00:58:56.950 align:middle line:90%
can do really well too.

00:58:56.950 --> 00:58:58.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Daniel Durda,
always a pleasure, my friend.

00:58:58.910 --> 00:58:59.380 align:middle line:84%
>>DURDA: Thanks a lot,
George, a lot of fun.

00:58:59.380 --> 00:59:01.255 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Daniel Durda,
here on Beyond Belief.

00:59:01.255 --> 00:59:04.205 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:04.205 --> 00:59:07.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Thank you.

00:59:07.610 --> 00:59:10.450 align:middle line:84%
Well, look, he's given us
some great information.

00:59:10.450 --> 00:59:12.320 align:middle line:90%
I have a simple theory.

00:59:12.320 --> 00:59:15.390 align:middle line:84%
Live every day like
it's your last.

00:59:15.390 --> 00:59:17.556 align:middle line:84%
Thanks for watching
Beyond Belief.

00:59:17.556 --> 00:59:22.020 align:middle line:90%
